{"info": {"author": "Opsy", "author_email": "", "bugtrack_url": null, "classifiers": ["Development Status :: 3 - Alpha", "Environment :: Web Environment", "Framework :: Flask", "Intended Audience :: System Administrators", "License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Operating System :: POSIX :: Linux", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.6", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.7", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.8", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3 :: Only", "Topic :: System :: Systems Administration"], "description": "# Opsy\nIt's Opsy! A simple multi-user/role operations inventory system with aspirations.\n\n# Developing\nIt's recommended to use a virtual environment for development.\n\n    $ mkvirtualenv -p /usr/bin/python3.6 opsy\n\nClone down the opsy repo:\n\n    $ git clone git@github.com:testeddoughnut/opsy.git\n\nInstall opsy for development (ensure you are in your previously created virtualenv):\n\n    $ pip install --editable .\n\nCreate opsy.toml by copying the example config:\n\n    $ cp opsy.toml.example opsy.toml\n\nInitialize the DB, the example config uses sqlite by default for development:\n\n    $ opsyctl db upgrade\n\nYou can now create your admin user and set its password, create a role, then add the user to the role:\n\n    $ opsyctl create-admin-user\n\nEach route is protected by a permission for that route. You can get a full list of the permissions by running `opsyctl permission-list`. Permissions are granted to roles and users gain access to permissions by being in roles. The admin user and role created with the last command are automatically granted full permissions.\n\nWe are now ready to start opsy for the first time:\n\n    $ opsyctl run\n\nBy default it listens on `http://127.0.0.1:5000/`. You can access the auto generated swagger docs by navigating to `http://127.0.0.1:5000/docs/`.\n\n# Dealing with schema changes\n\nIf you are introducing a change that requires a schema change you must create a schema revision. This can be done like so:\n\n    $ opsyctl db migrate\n\nThis will autogenerate a new revision file under `migrations/versions/`. Please review the resulting file and make any changes necessary to account for changes that Alembic doesn't do a good job of detecting (things like table renames). Please review the following documentation for more information:\nhttps://alembic.sqlalchemy.org/en/latest/autogenerate.html#what-does-autogenerate-detect-and-what-does-it-not-detect\n\nIf you are upgrading Opsy and need to migrate to a newer version of the schema you can run the following:\n\n    $ opsyctl db upgrade\n\n\n\n", "description_content_type": "text/markdown", "docs_url": null, "download_url": "", "downloads": {"last_day": -1, "last_month": -1, "last_week": -1}, "home_page": "https://github.com/testeddoughnut/opsy", "keywords": "", "license": "MIT", "maintainer": "", "maintainer_email": "", "name": "Opsy", "package_url": "https://pypi.org/project/Opsy/", "platform": "", "project_url": "https://pypi.org/project/Opsy/", "project_urls": {"Homepage": "https://github.com/testeddoughnut/opsy"}, "release_url": "https://pypi.org/project/Opsy/0.3.0/", "requires_dist": ["aiohttp (==3.5.1)", "apispec (==2.0.2)", "cheroot (==8.0.0)", "Flask (==1.1.1)", "flask-allows (==0.7.1)", "flask-apispec (==0.8.4)", "Flask-JSGlue (==0.3.1)", "flask-ldap3-login (==0.9.16)", "Flask-Login (==0.4.1)", "flask-marshmallow (==0.10.1)", "Flask-Migrate (==2.5.2)", "Flask-SQLAlchemy (==2.4.0)", "marshmallow (==3.2.1)", "marshmallow-sqlalchemy (==0.17.0)", "pbr (==5.1.1)", "prometheus-flask-exporter (==0.12.1)", "psycopg2-binary (==2.8.2)", "pyOpenSSL (==19.0.0)", "python-dateutil (==2.7.5)", "stevedore (==1.30.0)", "toml (==0.10.0)", "webargs (==5.3.2)", "coverage (==4.5.4) ; extra == 'test'", "Faker (==2.0.0) ; extra == 'test'", "pycodestyle (==2.4.0) ; extra == 'test'", "pydocstyle (==3.0.0) ; extra == 'test'", "pylint (==2.3.0) ; extra == 'test'", "pylint-flask (==0.6) ; extra == 'test'", "pytest (==5.0.1) ; extra == 'test'", "pytest-cov (==2.7.1) ; extra == 'test'", "pytest-flask (==0.15.0) ; extra == 'test'", "pytest-flask-sqlalchemy (==1.0.2) ; extra == 'test'", "pytest-mock (==1.11.0) ; extra == 'test'", "requests (==2.22.0) ; extra == 'test'", "tox (==3.13.2) ; extra == 'test'"], "requires_python": "", "summary": "A multi-user/role inventory system", "version": "0.3.0", "yanked": false, "html_description": "<div class=\"project-description\">\n            <h1>Opsy</h1>\n<p>It's Opsy! A simple multi-user/role operations inventory system with aspirations.</p>\n<h1>Developing</h1>\n<p>It's recommended to use a virtual environment for development.</p>\n<pre><code>$ mkvirtualenv -p /usr/bin/python3.6 opsy\n</code></pre>\n<p>Clone down the opsy repo:</p>\n<pre><code>$ git clone git@github.com:testeddoughnut/opsy.git\n</code></pre>\n<p>Install opsy for development (ensure you are in your previously created virtualenv):</p>\n<pre><code>$ pip install --editable .\n</code></pre>\n<p>Create opsy.toml by copying the example config:</p>\n<pre><code>$ cp opsy.toml.example opsy.toml\n</code></pre>\n<p>Initialize the DB, the example config uses sqlite by default for development:</p>\n<pre><code>$ opsyctl db upgrade\n</code></pre>\n<p>You can now create your admin user and set its password, create a role, then add the user to the role:</p>\n<pre><code>$ opsyctl create-admin-user\n</code></pre>\n<p>Each route is protected by a permission for that route. You can get a full list of the permissions by running <code>opsyctl permission-list</code>. Permissions are granted to roles and users gain access to permissions by being in roles. The admin user and role created with the last command are automatically granted full permissions.</p>\n<p>We are now ready to start opsy for the first time:</p>\n<pre><code>$ opsyctl run\n</code></pre>\n<p>By default it listens on <code>http://127.0.0.1:5000/</code>. You can access the auto generated swagger docs by navigating to <code>http://127.0.0.1:5000/docs/</code>.</p>\n<h1>Dealing with schema changes</h1>\n<p>If you are introducing a change that requires a schema change you must create a schema revision. This can be done like so:</p>\n<pre><code>$ opsyctl db migrate\n</code></pre>\n<p>This will autogenerate a new revision file under <code>migrations/versions/</code>. Please review the resulting file and make any changes necessary to account for changes that Alembic doesn't do a good job of detecting (things like table renames). Please review the following documentation for more information:\n<a href=\"https://alembic.sqlalchemy.org/en/latest/autogenerate.html#what-does-autogenerate-detect-and-what-does-it-not-detect\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://alembic.sqlalchemy.org/en/latest/autogenerate.html#what-does-autogenerate-detect-and-what-does-it-not-detect</a></p>\n<p>If you are upgrading Opsy and need to migrate to a newer version of the schema you can run the following:</p>\n<pre><code>$ opsyctl db upgrade\n</code></pre>\n\n          </div>"}, "last_serial": 6611449, "releases": {"0.0.1.dev166": [], "0.3.0": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "4ee21e6ce10503e59cd450f1ffb5e9c2", "sha256": "2d0872bde8fe94195111910617ef24a6242866d7a1a3dfc349d6cccee975984b"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "Opsy-0.3.0-py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "4ee21e6ce10503e59cd450f1ffb5e9c2", "packagetype": "bdist_wheel", "python_version": "py3", "requires_python": null, "size": 37023, "upload_time": "2020-01-07T23:08:56", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2020-01-07T23:08:56.131763Z", "url": "https://files.pythonhosted.org/packages/14/17/03b550c407f0e82a81f8ca8311811af1a7c9bc601c01d3a3d2af068c0082/Opsy-0.3.0-py3-none-any.whl", "yanked": false}, {"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "2f1b766f82cf4aa35492817eb216889b", "sha256": "218cef004ee952d2f1123f521fad74614067acc874ef8144979ae3c3773b44b9"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "Opsy-0.3.0.tar.gz", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "2f1b766f82cf4aa35492817eb216889b", "packagetype": "